Now I have a good picture. Let me plan and implement.

## Component Plan: Team Messaging Chat

### Component Tree
```
Chat.razor                    (page — owns all state, orchestrates layout)
├── ChannelList.razor         (left sidebar — channel list)
│   └── ChannelItem.razor     (single channel entry)
├── MessageArea.razor         (main center — messages + input)
│   ├── MessageItem.razor     (single message with reactions/actions)
│   └── MessageInput.razor    (textarea + send button)
└── ThreadPanel.razor         (right panel — thread view)


```

I'll build these components bottom-up, starting with the leaf components and working toward the page container, then add styling once the structure is in place.

For the data flow, the Chat page will manage the core state—channels, selected channel, messages, thread information, and pagination—while each sub-component handles its own interactions through event callbacks. ChannelList will notify when a channel is selected, MessageArea will handle thread opens, reactions, pagination, and message sending, and ThreadPanel will manage thread replies and closing. I'll also add a helper for formatting relative timestamps.

```

csharp
// ChannelItem.razor
@if (Channel != null)
{
    <div class="channel-item @(IsActive ? "active" : "")" @onclick="OnSelected.InvokeAsync">
        <div class="channel-name">#@Channel.Name</div>
        @if (!string.IsNullOrEmpty(Channel.Description))
        {
            <div class="channel-description">@Channel.Description</div>
        }
        @if (Channel.UnreadCount > 0)
        {
            <span class="unread-badge">@Channel.UnreadCount</span>
        }
    </div>
}

@code {
    [Parameter]
    public Channel Channel { get; set; }

    [Parameter]
    public bool IsActive { get; set; }

    [Parameter]
    public EventCallback OnSelected { get; set; }
}
```

I'll also add the import to _Imports.razor and create the CSS isolation file for the Chat page to handle the three-column layout. For ThreadPanel, I need the root message and thread messages, plus callbacks to close and send replies. Now I'm ready to implement everything in the Chat.razor page, which will own all the state and manage the selected channel, messages, and thread pagination through the IChatService.

I'm realizing the ThreadSummary record exists but there's no API method to fetch them, so I'll need to derive thread information from the messages themselves by looking at which ones have ReplyToId set. tracks thread info. For now, I'll keep it simple: the MessageItem component receives an optional ThreadSummary parameter, and the Chat page maintains a dictionary to track this data. When we fetch messages, I can examine them to identify thread starters, and populate the summaries when thread data becomes available. Let me add a

Adding thread tracking structure... I'll keep this simple by adding a `ThreadSummary?` parameter to MessageItem so the page can track thread data in a dictionary. When we don't have the data yet, it stays null and no replies link appears—once a thread is opened, we update the summary. Now I'm ready to write out all the component files with CSS isolation on the Chat component.

Writing component code... Writing component markup... Building the message reactions and thread display... Setting up the component parameters for thread callbacks and emoji reactions, then defining the emoji picker toggle and selection logic along with a helper for formatting timestamps. Building the message display component... I'm deciding between a simple "Load older messages" button versus implementing proper scroll-to-top detection with JS interop. Since the user specifically asked for scroll-to-top loading, I should do it properly with a collocated JavaScript module that detects when the user scrolls to the top and triggers the load callback.

Building the component files now... Finishing the component markup and defining the parameters for the thread display, then implementing a helper function to format timestamps in a human-readable way. Building the chat layout... When a channel is selected, I'm loading its messages with pagination, clearing any active thread view, marking it as read, and updating the unread count locally to reflect that change.

Now I'm adding methods to handle loading older messages by fetching them in batches and prepending them to the list, sending new messages to the selected channel, and opening a thread by finding the root message.

Continuing with thread operations—I'm fetching the thread messages, updating a summary with the message count and latest timestamp, then implementing close and reply functionality to manage the thread state and add responses. Writing component styles...

I'm thinking through the architecture more carefully now. Each sub-component should have its own CSS isolation file rather than cramming everything into one stylesheet. I also need a TimeHelper utility to avoid repeating the relative time formatting logic across components. For handling older messages, I'll implement a "Load older" button at the top with JavaScript interop to detect when users scroll near the top, and I'll attach the interop module directly to the MessageArea component.

Now I'm ready to create all the necessary files in batches.

Let me start by setting up the directory structure and then I'll need to check the MainLayout to see how to properly integrate the chat page, since it might already have navigation that I need to work around.

